This paper discusses the bias in the Journal Impact Factor (JIF), which is a measure of the impact of academic journals in a particular field. The paper does not focus on a specific area of computer science, but rather on the methodology used to evaluate the impact of journals. Therefore, it could be relevant to several sub-categories of computer science, such as digital libraries (cs.DL), information retrieval (cs.IR), cryptography (cs.CR), social and information networks (cs.SI), and computers and society (cs.CY).
